==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|abord}}, from {{m|enm|a-||on}} + {{m|enm|bord||board, side of a ship}}. (Equivalent to {{prefix|en|a|board}}.)

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əˈbɔːd/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/əˈbɔɹd/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-aboard.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

[[File:US Navy 111116-N-RI884-003 Sailors aboard the guided-missile destroyer USS O'Kane (DDG 77) prepare for an underway replenishment.jpg|thumb|Sailors '''aboard''' the USS O'Kane.]]

===Adverb===
{{en-adv|-}}

# [[on board|On board]]; into or within a ship or boat; hence, into or within a [[railway]] car. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=6}}</ref>
#: ''We all climbed '''aboard'''.''
# On or onto a horse, a camel, etc. {{defdate|First attested in the late 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''To sling a saddle '''aboard'''.''
# {{lb|en|baseball}} [[on base|On base]]. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 20<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''He doubled with two men '''aboard''', scoring them both.''
# Into a team, group, or company. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 20<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''The office manager welcomed him '''aboard'''.''
# {{lb|en|nautical}} [[alongside|Alongside]]. {{defdate|First attested from around (1350 to 1470).}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''The ships came close '''aboard''' to pass messages.''
#: ''The captain laid his ship '''aboard''' the enemy's ship.''

